               <p>CATHERINE CALDWELL. I <rs id="t18280410-91-viclabel505" type="occupation">keep the <placeName id="t18280410-91-crimeloc506">Canteen public-house at Hounslow barracks</placeName>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-91-crimeloc506" type="placeName" value="Canteen public-house at Hounslow barracks"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-91-crimeloc506" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                     <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280410-91-off503 t18280410-91-crimeloc506"></join>
                  </rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280410-91-victim638 t18280410-91-viclabel505"></join>. I did not miss these pots, but I know them to be mine.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. CRESSWELL. Q. You have a great many troops there? A. Yes - they are not very careful of pots and measures, they never take them off the premises - but when the troops leave there is a general turn out; I do not know whether any articles are ever thrown over the wall of the barracks - we send there regularly twice a day for pots; there is a possibility, certainly, that these might have been thrown away.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-91-person639">
                  JOHN 
                  EMMERSON
               <interp inst="t18280410-91-person639" type="surname" value="EMMERSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-91-person639" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-91-person639" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. I was at Fulham on the 1st of March and saw the prisoner with these pots in a bag; I asked what he had got - he said it was the first time he ever stole anything in his life.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Are you sure he used the word stole? A. Yes - I had seen him about the barracks the day before.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. They were thrown over the wall, and I took them up in the battered state they are now.</p>
